Presentation: Scoring Model for Predicting Corporate Bankruptcies

Context

Predicting corporate bankruptcies is a critical task for investors, financial institutions, and companies themselves. Accurate predictions help mitigate risks, allocate resources efficiently, and prevent significant losses. This project focuses on building a scoring model to predict the likelihood of default for publicly traded U.S. companies.

Expected Results

  • Identify companies with a high risk of default with satisfactory accuracy.

  • Gain deeper insights into the factors influencing bankruptcy likelihood.

  • Propose a practical solution for managing financial risks.

# CRSP monthly daily file (v2 format)
dsf_db <- tbl(wrds, in_schema("crsp","dsf_v2"))

# identifying information

stksecurityinfohist_db <- tbl(wrds, in_schema("crsp","stksecurityinfohist"))


permnos <- stksecurityinfohist_db %>%
  distinct(permno) %>%
  pull(permno)

batch_size <- 500
batches <- ceiling(length(permnos) / batch_size)

for (j in 1:batches) {
  print(j)
  permno_batch <- permnos[
    ((j - 1) * batch_size + 1):min(j * batch_size, length(permnos))
    ]
  crsp_daily_sub <- dsf_db %>%
    filter(permno %in% permno_batch) %>%
    filter(dlycaldt >= start_date & dlycaldt <= end_date) %>%
    inner_join(
      stksecurityinfohist_db %>%
        filter(sharetype == "NS" &
               securitytype == "EQTY" &
               securitysubtype == "COM" &
               usincflg == "Y" &
               issuertype %in% c("ACOR", "CORP") &
               primaryexch %in% c("N", "A", "Q") &
               conditionaltype %in% c("RW", "NW") &
               tradingstatusflg == "A") %>%
        select(permno, secinfostartdt, secinfoenddt),
      join_by(permno)
      ) %>%
    filter(dlycaldt >= secinfostartdt & dlycaldt <= secinfoenddt) %>%
    select(permno,

           date = dlycaldt,

           low = dlylow,

           ask = dlyask,
           open = dlyopen,
           ret = dlyret) %>%
    collect() # %>%
    # drop_na() # this causes common stocks like IBM with NA bid/ask to be removed from#
  if (nrow(crsp_daily_sub) > 0) {

                 "crsp_daily",

                 overwrite = ifelse(j == 1, TRUE, FALSE),

Step 2: Constructing the target variable (Y)

The aim is to classify companies into two groups, âhealthyâ and âunhealthy,â based on the variable dlrsn. âUnhealthyâ companies are those where dlrsn equals 2 or 3, while all other companies are classified as âhealthy.â For each group, relevant financial data is extracted from a historical database, and key financial ratios (such as WCTA, RETA, EBTA, TLTA, and SLTA) are calculated to evaluate financial health. For âunhealthyâ companies, a binary indicator Y is assigned, where Y = 1 for companies that are bankrupt in the most recent financial year, and Y = 0 otherwise. Finally, the two groups are merged into a unified dataset called companies, providing a comprehensive resource for analyzing financial performance and corporate health.

unhealthy_companies <- company_db %>%
  filter(as.integer(dlrsn)==2| as.integer(dlrsn)==3) %>% #filter(!is.na(dlrsn))
  select(conm, gvkey, dlrsn, dldte, fyrc) %>%
  collect() %>%
  inner_join(funda_db %>%
    filter(fyear >= 1960, at != 0) %>%
    select(gvkey, fyear, datadate, fdate, fyr, ceq, ni, act, lct, rect, oancf, capx, conm, at, wcap, re, ebit, lt, sale, invt, seq, cogs) %>%
    mutate(WCTA = wcap / at,
           RETA = re / at,
           EBTA = ebit / at,
           TLTA = lt / at,  # proxy for ME/TL
           SLTA = sale / at) %>%
  group_by(conm) %>%
  window_order(desc(fyear)) %>%
  mutate(Y = if_else(row_number() == 1, 1, 0)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
     collect(), by = c("conm", "gvkey")) %>%
  distinct(conm, fyear, .keep_all = TRUE)  # Remove duplicates
healthy_companies <- company_db %>% 
  filter(as.integer(dlrsn)!= 2 | as.integer(dlrsn) != 3) %>% 
  select(conm, gvkey, dlrsn, dldte, fyrc) %>%
  collect() %>%
  inner_join(funda_db %>% filter(fyear > 1960, at !=0) %>% select(gvkey, fyear, datadate, fdate, fyr, ceq, ni, act, lct, rect, oancf, capx, conm, at, wcap, re, ebit, lt, sale, invt, seq, cogs)%>% mutate(WCTA =wcap/at,
       RETA =re/at,
       EBTA = ebit/at,
       TLTA = lt/at,
       SLTA = sale/at) %>% 
    mutate(Y = 0) %>%
    collect(), by = c("conm", "gvkey")) %>%
  distinct(conm, fyear, .keep_all = TRUE)  # Remove duplicates
companies <- bind_rows(healthy_companies, unhealthy_companies)
saveRDS(companies, "companies.rds")

Lopucki

To finalize the creation of our bankruptcy indicator, we will leverage the LoPucki database. Known for its comprehensive and detailed data, LoPucki is the premier resource for in-depth research on large-scale U.S. corporate bankruptcies, judicial processes, and restructurings. Its unique datasets provide valuable insights into corporate failure patterns and legal outcomes, making it an indispensable tool for constructing a robust and accurate indicator of corporate bankruptcy. By incorporating data from LoPucki, we ensure the reliability and depth of our analysis in the context of financial distress and insolvency.

lopucki <- readxl::read_xlsx(
"default_data/Bankruptcy - LoPucki/Florida-UCLA-LoPucki Bankruptcy Research Database 1-12-2023.xlsx")
# Some companies fill multiple time (eg American Apparel)
lopucki %>%
group_by(GvkeyBefore) %>%
mutate(n=n()) %>%
ungroup() %>%
filter(n>1)

# Extract Chapter 7/11
# When multiple filings for a company (ie gvkey) you can select the min date (bankruptcy filings sometimes occur multiple times spanning up to a 10 year period)
lopucki_clean <- lopucki %>%
select(NameCorp, Chapter, GvkeyBefore, DateFiled) %>%
filter(Chapter %in% c('7', '11')) %>%
group_by(GvkeyBefore) %>%
summarize(DateFiled = min(DateFiled),

NameCorp = NameCorp[which.min(DateFiled)],
Chapter = Chapter[which.min(DateFiled)]) %>%
mutate(DateFiled = lubridate::as_date(DateFiled)) %>%
ungroup()

Construction of the final dataset with Y_lopucki

# Merge `final` with Lopucki dataset to check for date consistency
final <- companies %>%
  left_join(lopucki_clean %>% select(GvkeyBefore, DateFiled), by = c("gvkey" = "GvkeyBefore")) %>%
  mutate(
    # Flag inconsistency if the dates differ between `dldte` and Lopuckiâs `DateFiled`
    inconsistent_dates = if_else(!is.na(DateFiled) & DateFiled != dldte, 1, 0)
  )
final_data <- final %>%
  mutate(
    # Liquidity Ratios
    current_ratio = act / lct,
    quick_ratio = (act - invt) / lct,
    
    # Leverage Ratios
    debt_to_equity = lt / seq,
    debt_ratio = lt / at,
    
    # Profitability Ratios
    return_on_assets = ni / at,
    return_on_equity = ni / seq,
    
    # Efficiency Ratios
    asset_turnover = sale / at,
    inventory_turnover = cogs / invt
    
    # Altman Z-Score Components
    #working_capital_to_assets = (act - lct) / at,
    #retained_earnings_to_assets = re / at,
    #ebit_to_assets = ebit / at,
    #sales_to_assets = sale / at
  )

In the following, we refine the bankruptcy indicator Y_lopucki by integrating data consistency checks and accounting for potential lags in bankruptcy reporting. Specifically, we consider a lag of one year, acknowledging that a company might have effectively failed in the previous year but was recorded as bankrupt in the following year. The logic ensures that if DateFiled is missing, Y_lopucki defaults to the value of Y. For cases with no inconsistencies (inconsistent_dates = 0), the indicator is directly aligned with Y. However, when inconsistencies exist (inconsistent_dates = 1), additional conditions evaluate the relationship between DateFiled, dldte, and the financial reporting date (datadate). These conditions handle scenarios where the bankruptcy filing year might differ from the observed financial distress year, ensuring that the indicator accounts for both earlier and later filing dates while marking ambiguous cases as NA. This nuanced approach strengthens the reliability of the bankruptcy indicator by addressing temporal discrepancies in reporting.

final_data <- final_data %>%
  mutate(
    Y_lopucki = case_when(
      # If DateFiled is NA, then Y_lopucki takes the value of Y
      is.na(DateFiled) ~ Y,
      
      # Case 1: If Y = 0 and inconsistent_dates = 0, then Y_lopucki = 0
      Y == 0 & inconsistent_dates == 0 ~ 0,
      
      # Case 2: If Y = 0 and inconsistent_dates = 1, check that DateFiled is not NA
      Y == 0 & inconsistent_dates == 1 & !is.na(DateFiled) & year(datadate) == year(DateFiled) - 1 ~ 1,
      Y == 0 & inconsistent_dates == 1 & !is.na(DateFiled) & year(datadate) < year(DateFiled) - 1 ~ 0,
      Y == 0 & inconsistent_dates == 1 & !is.na(DateFiled) & year(datadate) > year(DateFiled) - 1 ~ NA_real_,
      
      # Case 3: If the year of dldte is equal to the year of DateFiled and inconsistent_dates = 1
      !is.na(dldte) & year(dldte) == year(DateFiled) & inconsistent_dates == 1 & year(datadate) == year(dldte) - 1 ~ 1,
      !is.na(dldte) & year(dldte) == year(DateFiled) & inconsistent_dates == 1 & year(datadate) < year(dldte) - 1 ~ 0,
      !is.na(dldte) & year(dldte) == year(DateFiled) & inconsistent_dates == 1 & year(datadate) > year(dldte) - 1 ~ NA_real_,
      
      # Case 4: If the year of dldte is greater than the year of DateFiled and inconsistent_dates = 1
      !is.na(dldte) & !is.na(DateFiled) & year(dldte) > year(DateFiled) & inconsistent_dates == 1 & year(datadate) == year(DateFiled) - 1 ~ 1,
      !is.na(dldte) & !is.na(DateFiled) & year(dldte) > year(DateFiled) & inconsistent_dates == 1 & year(datadate) < year(DateFiled) - 1 ~ 0,
      !is.na(dldte) & !is.na(DateFiled) & year(dldte) > year(DateFiled) & inconsistent_dates == 1 & year(datadate) > year(DateFiled) - 1 ~ NA_real_,
      
      # Default case: NA for all other scenarios
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    )
  )

Study of NA

# Function to analyze NA
analyze_na <- function(data) {
  # Calculate the number and percentage of NA per column
  na_summary <- sapply(data, function(col) sum(is.na(col)))
  na_percentage <- sapply(data, function(col) mean(is.na(col)) * 100)
  
  na_df <- data.frame(
    Column = names(data),
    NA_Count = na_summary,
    NA_Percentage = na_percentage
  )
  
  # Filter columns with NA and sort by percentage
  na_df <- na_df %>%
    filter(NA_Count >= 0) %>%
    arrange(desc(NA_Percentage))
  
  print(paste("Missing Values Analysis -"))
  print(na_df)
  
  ggplot(na_df, aes(x = reorder(Column, -NA_Percentage), y = NA_Percentage)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "skyblue") +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(
      title = paste("Percentage of Missing Values"),
      x = "Columns",
      y = "NA Percentage (%)"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()
}

Initially, we analyzed the distribution of missing values (NA) in the dataset and removed columns with more than 50% missing data. These columns were deemed uninformative and too challenging to impute reliably. Next, we performed multiple imputation using the pmm (Predictive Mean Matching) method for variables with less than 50% missing data. This approach allowed us to fill in the missing values by leveraging the statistical relationships between the remaining variables. However, after the multiple imputation, some variables, specifically quick_ratio, debt_ratio, and asset_turnover, still contained NA values. In a prior analysis, we had observed that these variables were highly correlated with others or provided similar information. As a result, their removal did not pose any issues and simplified the dataset while preserving its integrity and relevance. The final dataset is now complete, ready for further analysis or modeling, with reliable and coherent data.

# Winsorizarion
winsorize <- function(x, lower = 0.01, upper = 0.99) {
  # Calculate lower and upper quantiles
  quantiles <- quantile(x, probs = c(lower, upper), na.rm = TRUE)
  # Cap values outside the quantile range
  pmin(pmax(x, quantiles[1]), quantiles[2])
}

df_clean <- df_cleaned %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric) & !c(Y_lopucki, fyear), ~ winsorize(., 0.2,0.8)))
boxplot(df_clean)
df_clean %>%
  pivot_longer(where(is.numeric)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = name, y = value)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip()

To address the issue of outliers in the dataset, we applied Winsorization to all numeric variables, excluding Y_lopucki and fyear, as these are not appropriate for such transformation. Specifically, we used the 20th and 80th percentiles as thresholds, effectively capping extreme values at these limits. This approach ensures that outliers are mitigated while preserving the overall distribution and relationships within the data. The use of Winsorization at these thresholds was chosen to balance the reduction of extreme values with the retention of important data variability. By focusing on this range, we can limit the influence of extreme values without resorting to complete removal or severe transformations, thereby maintaining the integrity of the dataset for subsequent analysis.

Step 4: Logistic regression model

The idea is to evaluate a logistic regression model for predicting Y_lopucki, that represents in our case bankruptcy/default status. The logistic regression is a common tool to predict default, as it is a binary classification task. Logistic regression outpupts probabilities between 0, and 1, indicating the likelihood of a company to default.

Although logistic regression may not handle extreme class imbalances very well, with class weighting, it can be an efficient model.

After splitting the dataset into a training set (years 2005â2015) and a test set (post-2015), we observed significant imbalances in the proportions of Y_lopucki values. Specifically, in the training set, 97.5% of observations correspond to Y_lopucki = 0, while only 0.9% correspond to Y_lopucki = 1. A similar imbalance was noted in the test set, where 95.8% of the observations have Y_lopucki = 0. Such extreme imbalances can lead to challenges in model fairness and predictive accuracy, as the model tends to heavily favor the majority class (Y_lopucki = 0) and may even predict only zeros in some cases.

This is reflected in the predictions on the test set, where all predictions were for Y_lopucki = 0 (11,624 observations). The Area Under the Curve (AUC) for the model was calculated as 0.6287, which indicates a poor discriminatory ability. However, this result is likely inflated due to the imbalanced dataset, as the model achieves high accuracy by disproportionately predicting Y_lopucki = 0.

To address this issue, we propose balancing the training dataset to ensure a fair representation of both classes. This adjustment should help improve the modelâs ability to correctly predict minority class observations (Y_lopucki = 1) and provide a more realistic measure of performance. The goal is to ensure that the modelâs predictions are not only accurate but also equitable across both classes.

To address the class imbalance in the training dataset, we applied a combination of oversampling and undersampling using the ROSE package (method = "both"). This approach ensures a balanced representation of both classes (Y_lopucki = 0 and Y_lopucki = 1) by increasing the instances of the minority class (Y_lopucki = 1) and slightly reducing the majority class (Y_lopucki = 0). The resulting training dataset maintains a balance while avoiding excessive duplication or reduction, making it more suitable for training a logistic regression model.

The logistic regression model trained on the balanced dataset was then evaluated on the original (unbalanced) test set. This adjustment improved the class prediction distribution, with the model predicting both Y_lopucki = 0 (6,153 observations) and Y_lopucki = 1 (5,471 observations), compared to previously predicting only zeros. Despite this improvement in the balance of predictions, the Area Under the Curve (AUC) remains similar to the previous model (AUC = 0.6279), indicating that while the model better accounts for both classes, its overall discriminatory power has not significantly improved.

This suggests that balancing the training data effectively addresses the prediction bias toward the majority class, but additional steps may be needed to enhance the modelâs performance. Potential next steps include testing alternative algorithms (e.g., random forests or gradient boosting), engineering new features, or exploring hyperparameter tuning to improve predictive accuracy and discrimination.

The evaluation of the logistic regression model trained on the balanced dataset reveals mixed results in terms of its predictive performance. The accuracy is 54.1%, indicating that just over half of the predictions align with the actual values. However, the precision is very low at 3.14%, suggesting that a significant proportion of the predicted Y_lopucki = 1 values are FALSE positives. Despite this, the recall is relatively high at 69.0%, meaning the model successfully identifies a majority of the actual Y_lopucki = 1 cases. The F1-score, which balances precision and recall, remains low at 6.0%, reflecting the overall poor balance between these metrics.

Step 5: Time-series cross-validation

The idea now is to run a time series analysis for each year between 2005 and 2024, using the logistic regression model to predict the likelihood of a company defaulting based on financial ratios, such as WCTA, RETA, EBTA, TLTA, SLTA.

For each iteration, we will split the dataset into training set (using all previous years) and a test set (using next year). Here, we train our model on the imbalanced dataset. We can see the proportions of each class in the training and test sets for each year, as well as an overview of model performance across all years.

years <- 2005:2024
results <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:(length(years) - 1)) {
  train_years <- years[1:i]
  test_year <- years[i + 1]
  
  train_data <- df_selected %>% filter(fyear %in% train_years)
  test_data <- df_selected %>% filter(fyear == test_year)
  
  # Check if we have value on the train and the test set
  if (nrow(train_data) == 0 | nrow(test_data) == 0) {
    next  
  }

  model <- glm(Y_lopucki ~ WCTA + RETA + EBTA + TLTA + SLTA, data = train_data, family = binomial())
  
  predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
  test_data$predicted_default <- ifelse(predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)
  
  
  if (all(test_data$predicted_default == 0, na.rm = TRUE) | 
      all(test_data$predicted_default == 1, na.rm = TRUE)) {
    precision <- NA
    recall <- NA
    f1_score <- NA
  } else {
    confusion <- table(test_data$Y_lopucki, test_data$predicted_default)
    precision <- confusion[2, 2] / sum(confusion[, 2])
    recall <- confusion[2, 2] / sum(confusion[2, ])
    f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
  }
  
  accuracy <- mean(test_data$predicted_default == test_data$Y_lopucki, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  results <- rbind(results, data.frame(test_year = test_year, 
                                       accuracy = accuracy, 
                                       precision = precision, 
                                       recall = recall, 
                                       f1_score = f1_score))
}

The following code also performs a time-series analisis of logistic regression models, by again evaluating each yearâs performance. This code balances the training data using oversampling before fitting the logistic regression model, using the function ovun.sumple() with the method="both", used to balance the classes by both oversampling the minority class and undersampling the majority

results <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:(length(years) - 1)) {
  train_years <- years[1:i]
  test_year <- years[i + 1]
  
  train_data <- df_selected %>% filter(fyear %in% train_years)
  test_data <- df_selected %>% filter(fyear == test_year)
  
  if (nrow(train_data) == 0 | nrow(test_data) == 0) {
    next
  }
  
  
  if (length(unique(test_data$Y_lopucki)) < 2) {
    cat("Warning: Test data for year", test_year, "does not contain both classes.\n")
    next
  }
  
  # Balance the training data using oversampling
  train_data_balanced <- ovun.sample(Y_lopucki ~ ., data = train_data, method = "both")$data

  model <- glm(Y_lopucki ~ WCTA + RETA + EBTA + TLTA + SLTA, data = train_data_balanced, family = binomial())

  predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
  test_data$predicted_default <- ifelse(predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)
  
  if (all(test_data$predicted_default == 0, na.rm = TRUE) | 
      all(test_data$predicted_default == 1, na.rm = TRUE)) {
    precision <- NA
    recall <- NA
    f1_score <- NA
  } else {
    confusion <- table(test_data$Y_lopucki, test_data$predicted_default)
    precision <- confusion[2, 2] / sum(confusion[, 2])
    recall <- confusion[2, 2] / sum(confusion[2, ])
    f1_score <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
  }
  
  accuracy <- mean(test_data$predicted_default == test_data$Y_lopucki, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  results <- rbind(results, data.frame(test_year = test_year, 
                                       accuracy = accuracy, 
                                       precision = ifelse(is.na(precision), 0, precision), 
                                       recall = ifelse(is.na(recall), 0, recall), 
                                       f1_score = ifelse(is.na(f1_score), 0, f1_score)))
}

Practical 2 - Feature Engineering/Distance to Default

Altmanâs Score Revisited

The Altman Z-Score is a financial model developed by Edward Altman in 1968, used to predict the likelihood of a company going bankrupt within two years.

The following code includes data preprocessing and analysis steps. We create new variables: (i) Earning Growth (earning_growth), compared to previous period. (ii) size - size of the company, measured in total assests at. (iii) Return on Assets (roa): calculates the profitability of a company relative to its total assets, computed as a ratio of net income to total assets.

We also compute the Market equity to Book liabilities Ratio (ME_BL). This variable is computed as ratio of the common equity (ceq) to the long-term debt (lt). This provides a measure of a companyâs financial leverage. We also apply some log transformation to some of the variables.

Next step is Winorization, when several variables (such as size, at, Log_MEBL, ME_BL, and roa) have limited extreme values (outliers). The winsorization process trims the values at the 20th and 80th percentiles, reducing the effect of extreme outliers on statistical analysis.

company_all <- readRDS("wrds_data/company_all.rds")
compustat_all <- readRDS("wrds_data/compustat_all_light.rds")
# We extract some variables from different datasets to create ratios that interest us, to include in the Altman's 2004 model
var_alt_age <- company_all %>%
  select(gvkey,incorp)

var_alt_dltt <- compustat_all %>%
  select(gvkey,dltt, xrd)

var_alt <- var_alt_age %>% 
  left_join(var_alt_dltt, by = "gvkey")

df_selected$at <- data$at
df_selected$gvkey <- final_data$gvkey
final_combined <- df_selected %>%
  left_join(var_alt, by = "gvkey", relationship = "many-to-many")
# We create the variables earnings_growth, size and roa
# earnings growth measures growth in earnings or net income
# size is the size of the company, measured by at, it's total assets
# roa measures profitability relative to total assets

final_combined <- final_combined %>%
  mutate(earnings_growth = (ni - lag(ni) / lag(ni)), size = at, roa = ni / at)
# Compute ME_BL (Market Equity to Book Liabilities Ratio)
final_combined <- final_combined %>%
  mutate(
    ME_BL = ceq / lt                 
  )

# Log-transform RETA and EBTA and ME_BL
final_combined <- final_combined %>%
  mutate(
    Log_RETA = ifelse(RETA < 1, -log(1 - RETA), NA),
    Log_EBTA = ifelse(EBTA < 1, -log(1 - EBTA), NA),
    Log_MEBL = 1 + log(ME_BL)
  )
df_final_combined <- final_combined %>% select(where(is.numeric) & !c(xrd,dltt,incorp, Y_lopucki))

In the Altman 1968 model, all predictors are statistically significant (p < 0.05), highlighting their importance in explaining default risk.

The coefficient for WCTA is -0.83700, indicating that higher working capital relative to total assets reduces the likelihood of default. This emphasizes the importance of liquidity, as companies with stronger liquidity are better able to manage their financial obligations and reduce the risk of distress.

The coefficient for RETA is -0.30282, suggesting that higher retained earnings relative to total assets decrease the likelihood of default. Retained earnings reflect accumulated profitability and financial stability, making such companies less vulnerable to financial distress.

EBTA has the most negative coefficient (-3.33297), highlighting the critical role of profitability. Companies with higher earnings before taxes relative to total assets are significantly less likely to default, underlining the importance of operational profitability in reducing financial vulnerability.

In contrast, TLTA has a positive coefficient of 2.57893, suggesting that higher leverage (liabilities relative to assets) increases the likelihood of default. This is consistent with financial theory, where excessive debt levels heighten financial vulnerability and increase default risk.

Finally, the coefficient for SLTA is 0.07479, a small positive value, indicating that higher sales efficiency slightly increases the likelihood of default. This might reflect that aggressive sales strategies, without adequate financial management, could lead to liquidity constraints or overextension.

The Merton Model (1974)

The Merton model, developed by Robert C. Merton in 1974 is another method used to estimate the default risk of a company. It is based on the structural approach to credit risk, where the value of a firmâs equity is treated as a call option on its assets.

We need to estimate the Distance to Default (DtD) and Default probability (PD) of companies. We start by calculating key financial metrics, and using both a naive and iterative approach we compute DtD and DP. We followed methodology described by Vassalou, 2004 method. The output shows us a comparison of the results from these two methods and visualizes the differences.

data <- df_selected

# Compute Default Point (DP) based on Vassalou (2004)

# Estimate equity volatility (sig_E) using historical returns
data <- data %>%
  group_by(gvkey) %>%
  arrange(datadate) %>%
  mutate(
    log_ret = ifelse(!is.na(lag(E)) & lag(E) > 0 & E > 0, log(E / lag(E)), NA)
, # Handle invalid values
    sig_E = ifelse(sum(!is.na(log_ret)) >= 60, sd(log_ret, na.rm = TRUE) * sqrt(252), NA)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()
# NaÃ¯ve Distance to Default (DtD_naive)
data <- data %>%
  mutate(
    sigma_D = 0.05 + 0.25 * sig_E, # Approximation for debt volatility
    sigma_V = ifelse(!is.na(E) & !is.na(D) & E + D > 0 & sigma_D > 0,
                     (E / (E + D)) * sig_E + (D / (E + D)) * sigma_D, NA),
    T = 1, # 1-year horizon
    r = ifelse(is.na(r), 0.01, r), # Fill missing risk-free rates with a default value
    DtD_naive = ifelse(!is.na(sigma_V) & sigma_V > 0 & D > 0 & E + D > 0,
                       (log((E + D) / D) + (r - 0.5 * sigma_V^2) * T) / (sigma_V * sqrt(T)), NA),
    PD_naive = ifelse(!is.na(DtD_naive), pnorm(-DtD_naive), NA)
  )
# PDF-Based Function for Iterative DtD Calculation
iterative_dtd_pdf <- function(data) {
  T <- 1
  iter_max <- 15
  tol <- 1e-4
  
  data <- data %>%
    filter(!is.na(E) & !is.na(D) & E > 0 & D > 0 & sig_E > 0) %>%
    mutate(
      V = E + D, # Initial asset value
      sig_V = sig_E * E / (E + D), # Initial asset volatility
      converged = FALSE, # Convergence flag
      iter = 0 # Iteration counter
    )
  
  for (i in 1:iter_max) {
    data <- data %>%
      mutate(
        d1 = (log(V / D) + (r + 0.5 * sig_V^2) * T) / (sig_V * sqrt(T)),
        d2 = d1 - sig_V * sqrt(T),
        V_new = (E + D * exp(-r * T) * pnorm(d2)) / pnorm(d1),
        sig_V_new = sd(log(V_new / lag(V_new, default = V_new[1])), na.rm = TRUE) * sqrt(252),
        error = abs(sig_V - sig_V_new),
        sig_V = ifelse(error < tol, sig_V, sig_V_new),
        V = ifelse(error < tol, V, V_new),
        converged = error < tol | converged,
        iter = iter + 1
      )
    if (all(data$converged)) break
  }
  
  data <- data %>%
    mutate(
      DtD = (log(V / D) + (r - 0.5 * sig_V^2) * T) / (sig_V * sqrt(T)),
      PD = pnorm(-DtD)
    ) %>%
    dplyr::select(gvkey, datadate, DtD, PD)
  
  return(data)
}
# Apply iterative DtD function using PDF method
iterative_results <- iterative_dtd_pdf(data)

# Join results back to the original dataset
data <- data %>%
  left_join(iterative_results, by = c("gvkey", "datadate"), relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  dplyr::rename(DtD_iterative = DtD, PD_iterative = PD)

# Summary statistics

Then, we add micro predictors (company-specific/ related to the stock price and returns). They include (i) Rolling volatility: rolling window of 60 periods to calculate the standard deviation of the log returns. This represents the measure of a stock price volatility over the past 60 periods. (ii) Momentum (3months): a rolling sum of the log returns over 60 periods.

After this, we fit the logistic regression to the new predictors.

# Micro variables

  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Normalization
normalize <- function(x) {
  if (!is.na(sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)) && sd(x, na.rm = TRUE) > 0) {
    (x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else {
    x 
  }
}

This code uses cross-validation to find the best penalty parameter (lambda) for a Lasso logistic regression model. The function cv.glmnet() tests multiple lambda values to identify the one that minimizes the error. The plot shows the binomial deviance for each lambda, with the dashed line marking the best lambda. The selected lambda, stored as best_lambda, is then used to fit the final Lasso model. This ensures the model focuses on the most important predictors while avoiding overfitting.

The code extracts the predictors selected by the Lasso model by identifying variables with non-zero coefficients. This code demonstrates the use of a relaxed Lasso model, which combines the properties of Ridge (alpha = 0) and Lasso (alpha = 1) regression by setting alpha = 0.5. This hybrid approach allows for some coefficients to be shrunk towards zero while retaining a level of flexibility to include correlated predictors that might be excluded by Lasso alone.

The coefficients printed show the contribution of each predictor to the model after applying this relaxed regularization. Variables like lt, sale, and TLTA have relatively high positive coefficients, suggesting a stronger positive association with the target variable, while variables like ni, return_on_assets, and ebit have large negative coefficients, indicating a negative relationship. This method provides a balance between variable selection and coefficient stability,

This code filters the predictors selected by the Lasso model based on a specified threshold for their absolute coefficient values. By setting a threshold of 0.01, only variables with an absolute coefficient value greater than 0.01 are retained. These thresholded variables represent the predictors with the most significant contributions to the model.

The resulting list includes variables like inventory_turnover, current_ratio, and lt, among others. This process allows for further refinement of the feature set by excluding variables with negligible impacts, ensuring that the final model focuses on the most meaningful predictors while reducing noise and enhancing interpretability.

Adjusting Financial Variables by Firm Size

Data Preparation

# Adjusting Financial Variables by Firm Size
df <- data %>%
  mutate(
    size = pmax(debt_to_equity, at, na.rm = TRUE),  # Firm size as max(debt-to-equity, total assets)
    WCTA_adj = WCTA / size,                        # Adjust WCTA by firm size
    RETA_adj = RETA / size,                        # Adjust RETA by firm size
    EBTA_adj = EBTA / size,                        # Adjust EBTA by firm size
    TLTA_adj = TLTA / size,                        # Adjust TLTA by firm size
    SLTA_adj = SLTA / size                         # Adjust SLTA by firm size
  )

Lasso model

# Prepare data for Lasso model
X <- model.matrix(Y_lopucki ~ WCTA_adj + RETA_adj + EBTA_adj + TLTA_adj + SLTA_adj, data = df)[, -1] 
y <- df$Y_lopucki

# Fit Lasso model
set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
lasso_model <- cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha = 1, family = "binomial")

# Optimal lambda value
optimal_lambda <- lasso_model$lambda.min
cat("Optimal Lambda:", optimal_lambda, "\n")
Optimal Lambda: 0.0001151543 
# Coefficients of the Lasso model
lasso_coefs <- coef(lasso_model, s = "lambda.min")
print(lasso_coefs)

This code implements a Lasso logistic regression model that adjusts financial variables by firm size to account for differences in scale. The financial ratios (WCTA, RETA, EBTA, TLTA, SLTA) are normalized by dividing each by the firmâs size, calculated as the maximum of debt_to_equity and total_assets. This ensures that the variables are comparable across firms of different sizes.

A Lasso regression is then fitted using cross-validation (cv.glmnet) to identify the optimal regularization parameter (lambda.min) that minimizes the modelâs binomial deviance. The coefficients of the model at this optimal lambda are extracted, showing which variables contribute most significantly to the predictions.

Random Search for Hyperparameter Tuning

set.seed(123)

# Define a random hyperparameter space
n_samples <- 20  # Number of random combinations to test
random_params <- data.frame(
  eta = runif(n_samples, 0.01, 0.1),               
  max_depth = sample(2:6, n_samples, replace = TRUE),  
  subsample = runif(n_samples, 0.6, 1),            
  colsample_bytree = runif(n_samples, 0.6, 1),     
  min_child_weight = sample(1:10, n_samples, replace = TRUE) 
)

# Initialize variables to track the best parameters
best_auc <- 0
best_params <- list()

# Random search loop
for (i in 1:n_samples) {
  params <- list(
    objective = "binary:logistic",
    eval_metric = "auc",
    eta = random_params$eta[i],
    max_depth = random_params$max_depth[i],
    subsample = random_params$subsample[i],
    colsample_bytree = random_params$colsample_bytree[i],
    min_child_weight = random_params$min_child_weight[i]
  )
  
  # Train using xgb.cv
  cv_results <- xgb.cv(
    params = params,
    data = dtrain,
    nfold = 5,
    nrounds = 300,
    early_stopping_rounds = 10,
    verbose = 0
  )
  
  # Extract the best AUC
  current_auc <- max(cv_results$evaluation_log$test_auc_mean)
  
  # Update the best parameters if this combination is better
  if (current_auc > best_auc) {
    best_auc <- current_auc
    best_params <- params
  }
}

print(paste("Best AUC:", best_auc))
print("Best Parameters:")
print(best_params)

Bayesian Optimization

# Define the scoring function for optimization
scoring_function <- function(eta, max_depth, subsample, colsample_bytree, min_child_weight) {
  params <- list(
    objective = "binary:logistic",
    eval_metric = "auc",
    eta = eta,
    max_depth = as.integer(max_depth),
    subsample = subsample,
    colsample_bytree = colsample_bytree,
    min_child_weight = min_child_weight
  )
  
  cv_results <- xgb.cv(
    params = params,
    data = dtrain,
    nfold = 5,
    nrounds = 300,
    early_stopping_rounds = 10,
    verbose = 0
  )
  
  # Return the maximum AUC as the score to maximize
  max(cv_results$evaluation_log$test_auc_mean)
}

# Run Bayesian optimization
set.seed(123)
bayes_results <- bayesOpt(
  FUN = scoring_function,
  bounds = list(
    eta = c(0.01, 0.1),
    max_depth = c(2L, 6L),
    subsample = c(0.6, 1),
    colsample_bytree = c(0.6, 1),
    min_child_weight = c(1, 10)
  ),
  initPoints = 10,
  iters.n = 20,
  acq = "ei"
)

# Best parameters from Bayesian optimization
print(bayes_results$scoreSummary)

2. Remove of constant variables. LDA requires variablility

# We have one constant variable, we need to remove this to perform LDA. As LDA requires variablility 
# Identify variables that are constant within groups
constant_vars <- sapply(train_data[-which(names(train_data) == "Y")], function(col) {
  length(unique(col[train_data$Y == 0])) == 1 && length(unique(col[train_data$Y == 1])) == 1
})

# Output names of constant variables
constant_cols <- names(constant_vars[constant_vars])
print(constant_cols)
[1] "Y_lopucki"
# Drop constant columns from the dataset
train_data <- train_data[, !names(train_data) %in% constant_cols]

3. Get Rid of Colinearity

# We have high colinearity. 
# Calculate the correlation matrix for numeric variables
# Filter numeric columns and compute the correlation matrix
numeric_data <- train_data %>%
  select_if(is.numeric)  # Select only numeric columns

cor_matrix <- cor(numeric_data, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")

# Find pairs of variables with high correlation (e.g., |correlation| > 0.9)
high_corr_pairs <- which(abs(cor_matrix) > 0.5, arr.ind = TRUE)
high_corr_pairs <- high_corr_pairs[high_corr_pairs[, 1] < high_corr_pairs[, 2], ]

# Identify variables to drop (keep only one variable from each highly correlated pair)
vars_to_drop <- unique(colnames(cor_matrix)[high_corr_pairs[, 2]])

# Drop collinear variables from train and test datasets
train_data <- train_data[, !(names(train_data) %in% vars_to_drop)]

test_data <- test_data[, !(names(test_data) %in% vars_to_drop)]

# Ensure the test dataset matches the train dataset
train_vars <- names(train_data)

test_data <- test_data[, names(test_data) %in% train_vars]
